As an introverted creative, being self-employed and valuing one's privacy highly should not be a contradiction, but it is sometimes. Most online resources and coaches advise working with the (bad) tech giants and behaving extrovertly. Advertise here, follow the algorithm, show your personality. Get a blue checkmark with that service, be available 24/7, answer inquiries with a video of yourself, respond immediately. Video, video, video.
1/3
For me, it's a year of changes.
I don't want to feed the tech giants with money, data, and my energy. Or coaches who have their own extroverted solution and try to sell it to everyone. I'm looking for new ways to run my business and at the same time I'm fighting my long-held belief that you have to do something in a certain way to be successful.
Wish me luck!
I've already taken the first steps.
I've cancelled Facebook, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and deleted my private WhatsApp account.
I also removed Google Analytics, the last external tracker, from my website yesterday and feel good about it.
Recently, I subscribed to a European CRM to have better DSGVO support, and I will relocate my business there in the next few weeks.
I've transferred my MX account to Proton and now have full SPF, DKIM, and DMARC, without having to pay Google for normal email validation.
3/3
